title: Approaches to Literature
subject: ENG
courseDesc: "Great Lit"  Do we read great literature to be educated? to be entertaine  d? To better understand oneself and the world? Hopefully, by   the end of the semester, you will know why it is we do so.  Reading the short novels, stories, poetry, and drama we'll   cover during the semester might reveal a piece of work that   "speaks" to you. When (or if) this happens, we'll explore  it, and at least one of the above questions will be answered  , maybe even some deeper ones. Literature can do that.

title: Approaches to Literature
subject: ENG
courseDesc: Great Screenplays! Great Narratives!  Without a script there aren't any great movies. But what    makes a movie great? Well, it starts with some writer  putting black letters on a white page. We'll concentrate   on the narrative structure of great, classic movies that  were adapted from great novels and short stories and  have been recognized as award-winning screenplays!

courseDesc: Writing Across Cultures-  Journalists are often called on to cross borders--not just  national ones, but borders of culture, identify, race,  religion, and other markers of identity. title: Honors Colloquium
subject: HON
courseDesc: This course will examine the lives and thought (through the  discussion of primary text selections) of Jane Addams (1860-  1935), Simone Weil (1909-1943), and Dorothy Day (1897-1980).  These three, roughly contemporaneous female writer-  activists all lived out their convictions in a shared  emphasis on praxis, focusing on a deliberate and principled  commitment to living with the marginalized in their struggle  for peace and social justice: Addams in the "social  experiment" of Hill House, Weil by working "under cover" in  factories, and Day as a journalist and founder of Catholic  Worker Movement.
